liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: While veteran economist Warren Hogan isn't calling a recession, AMP deputy chief economist sees things differently. Diana Mousina predicts that Australia will experience a per capita recession over the coming quarters. That where GDP growth per person is negative for two quarters, as opposed to the overall economy contracting over six months, which is the technical definition of a recession. And a "real" recession could be on the cards if the RBA keeps raising interest rates. "The RBA's hawkiness and subsequent likelihood of another interest rate hike in July or August means a "real" recession is a high possibility in the next 12 to 18 months," Ms Mousina said. "In our view, the RBA is taking interest rates too high and doesn't need to generate a recession and pain on households to get inflation down at a time when any of the forward looking inflation indicators are already pointing to lower price growth in the next 6 months."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: AMP sees rate hike recession

children.content: While veteran economist Warren Hogan isn't calling a recession,
AMP deputy chief economist sees things differently.
Diana Mousina predicts that Australia will experience a per capita recession over the coming quarters.
That where GDP growth per person is negative for two quarters, as opposed to the overall economy contracting over six months, which is the technical definition of a recession.
And a "real" recession could be on the cards if the RBA keeps raising interest rates.
"The RBA's hawkiness and subsequent likelihood of another interest rate hike in July or August means a "real" recession is a high possibility in the next 12 to 18 months," Ms Mousina said.

"In our view, the RBA is taking interest rates too high and doesn't need to generate a recession and pain on households to get inflation down at a time when any of the forward looking inflation indicators are already pointing to lower price growth in the next 6 months."

props.alt: Graph showing real gdp per capita growth

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Economist Warren Hogan, managing director of EQ Economics, says higher interest rates are doing their job by dampening demand and slowing the economy. "The economy is slowing in line with both the government's and the RBA's desire to try and execute a soft landing to avoid a damaging recession," he says. However, other economists think the RBA has gone too far in raising interest rates and that could tip the Australian economy into a recession. But Mr Hogan told Alicia Barry on the ABC News Channel that he doesn't think that will happen despite the pull back in spending and savings by households. "We are getting the slowdown, and of course, no signs of recession, very orderly, and of course with the rate hikes that we've seen since this quarter, I think we can be comfortable that we are going to see a further softness in the economy which hopefully will see inflation really start to fall down through the back half of this year without too many further rate hikes."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Will there be a recession in Australia?
